[{"location":"portfolio/#Portfolios","page":"Portfolios","title":"Portfolios","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"portfolio/","page":"Portfolios","title":"Portfolios","text":"Cholesky-variate distributions are distributions whose variate forms are CholeskyVariate. This means each draw is a factorization of a positive-definite matrix of type LinearAlgebra.Cholesky (the object produced by the function LinearAlgebra.cholesky applied to a dense positive-definite matrix.)","category":"page"},{"location":"portfolio/#Portfolios-2","page":"Portfolios","title":"Portfolios","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"portfolio/","page":"Portfolios","title":"Portfolios","text":"Arcsine","category":"page"},{"location":"portfolio/#Index","page":"Portfolios","title":"Index","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"portfolio/","page":"Portfolios","title":"Portfolios","text":"Pages = [\"cholesky.md\"]","category":"page"},{"location":"backtesting/#Backtesting","page":"Backtesting","title":"Backtesting","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"backtesting/#Walk-Forward-Analysis","page":"Backtesting","title":"Walk-Forward Analysis","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"backtesting/","page":"Backtesting","title":"Backtesting","text":"walk_forward","category":"page"},{"location":"backtesting/#Index","page":"Backtesting","title":"Index","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"backtesting/","page":"Backtesting","title":"Backtesting","text":"Pages = [\"backtesting.md\"]","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"MPT","title":"MPT","text":"CurrentModule = MPT","category":"page"},{"location":"#MPT","page":"MPT","title":"MPT","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"MPT","title":"MPT","text":"Documentation for MPT.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"MPT","title":"MPT","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"MPT","title":"MPT","text":"Modules = [MPT]","category":"page"},{"location":"#MPT.equal_weights-Tuple{AbstractMatrix}","page":"MPT","title":"MPT.equal_weights","text":"Arcsine(a,b)\n\nThe Arcsine distribution has probability density function\n\nf(x) = frac1pi sqrt(x - a) (b - x) quad x in a b\n\nArcsine()        # Arcsine distribution with support [0, 1]\nArcsine(b)       # Arcsine distribution with support [0, b]\nArcsine(a, b)    # Arcsine distribution with support [a, b]\nparams(d)        # Get the parameters, i.e. (a, b)\nminimum(d)       # Get the lower bound, i.e. a\nmaximum(d)       # Get the upper bound, i.e. b\nlocation(d)      # Get the left bound, i.e. a\nscale(d)         # Get the span of the support, i.e. b - a\n\nExternal links\n\nArcsine distribution on Wikipedia\n\nUse Arcsine(a, b, check_args=false) to bypass argument checks.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MPT.walk_forward-Tuple{DataFrames.AbstractDataFrame, Any, Int64}","page":"MPT","title":"MPT.walk_forward","text":"walk_forward(returns::AbstractDataFrame, func, rebalancing::Int)\n\nThe Arcsine distribution has probability density function\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"}]
